{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640116"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:12:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17802"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17802"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72446"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10516"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10193"},{"type":"tags","id":"10195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72446"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hair growth cycle consists of distinct phases that regulate the growth and shedding of hair. Each follicle cycles independently through these phases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the catagen phase of the hair cycle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shedding of the old hair shaft","Active growth and melanin production","Formation of a new hair bulb","Regression of the hair follicle with upward movement","Complete rest phase with no activity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eregression of the hair follicle with upward movement\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the catagen phase. During this transitional phase, cell division stops, the hair bulb separates from the dermal papilla, and the follicle moves toward the surface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShedding of the old hair shaft\u003C/strong\u003E describes the exogen phase when the old hair is released from the follicle.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive growth and melanin production\u003C/strong\u003E describes the anagen phase where the hair actively grows and pigment is produced.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of a new hair bulb\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the early anagen phase as the growth cycle begins again.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete rest phase with no activity\u003C/strong\u003E describes the telogen phase where the follicle rests before the next cycle begins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe catagen phase is relatively brief, lasting only two to three weeks. During this time, programmed cell death (apoptosis) causes the lower portion of the hair follicle to regress while the dermal papilla remains intact for the next cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The catagen phase of the hair cycle is a transitional phase characterised by cessation of cell division and regression of the hair follicle.","During catagen, the hair bulb detaches from the dermal papilla and moves upward in the follicle.","The catagen phase typically lasts two to three weeks and affects about 1% of scalp hairs at any time."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17802"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:46:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:47:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10516"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72446"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-1